Graphical abstract The series of nickel(II) and copper(II) complexes (3a–f) bearing tetradentate [ONNO] β-ketoiminato ligands, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-o-phenylenediamine 2a, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-ethylenediamine 2b, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-trans-1,2-cyclohexanediamine 2c, have been synthesized and characterized. X-ray crystal structures of complexes 3a–c and 3e–f reveal that each central metal adopts an almost square planar coordination geometry. Upon activation with methylaluminoxane (MAO), the nickel(II) complexes 3a–c display high catalytic activities for the vinyl polymerization of norbornene (NB), yielding high molecular weights of the polynorbornene (PNB), especially the complex 3b (24.46×105 gPNB/molNi h). While copper(II) complexes 3d–f only traces of PNB are generated. The catalytic system 3b/MAO is chosen for further investigations under various polymerization parameters. Keywords β-Ketoiminato Nickel Copper Norbornene Vinyl polymerization 1 Introduction Polynorbornene (PNB) was synthesized via vinyl polymerization, which has been widely used in microelectronics industry for its unique properties [1–3]. Vinyl polymerization of norbornene (NB) was obtained firstly using TiCl4-based Ziegler catalyst, but these and subsequent zirconocene/MAO catalytic systems performed with very low activities [4–6]. Thereafter, late transition metal catalysts were subsequently described with high activities for olefin polymerization, and they possess lower oxophilicity and greater tolerant for polar functional monomers compared to the early transition metal catalysts [7–11]. In particular, the catalysts based on the bulky α-diimine, bis(imino)pyridine and salicylaldiminato ligands were reported and successfully applied to olefin polymerization with high catalytic activities [12–14]. The series of late transition metal catalysts for olefin polymerization have aroused great interest. Driven by academic and commercial considerations, various ligands such as bidentate ligand N^N [15–19], N^O [20–25], N^P [26,27], P^P [28,29], and tridentate ligand N^N^N [30,31], N^N^O [32–34], N^P^N [35,36] were designed. Especially the complexes bearing bidentate N^O ligands have been catched much attention. These catalytic systems were effective for polymerization of NB. The majority of the present nickel and copper complexes were based on bidentate and tridentate ligands. But the complexes with tetradentate ligands were scarcely reported [37,38]. Inspired by four-coordinated complexes bearing bis(β-ketoiminato) ligands, which were employed in polymerization of NB with high catalytic activities [39–42], we are interested in the complexes bearing tetradentate β-ketoiminato ligands. Considering various structures of the complexes may have significant impacts on the catalytic activity and the property of polymer, we designed and synthesized tetradentate β-ketoiminato complexes (3a–f), and their vinyl polymerization of NB behavior is also investigated in detail. The nickel(II) complexes (3a–c) display high catalytic activities for the vinyl polymerization of NB in the presence of MAO as cocatalyst, obtaining high molecular weighs of PNBs. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials All manipulations involving air- or moisture-sensitive compounds were carried out under nitrogen atmosphere by the standard Schlenk techniques. dichloromethane was purified over calcium hydride and distilled under nitrogen prior to use. Ethanol was dried by heating over iodine-activated magnesium (0.5–5.0g/L). Norbornene was purchased from Alfa Aesar and purified by distillation over sodium. Methylaluminoxane (MAO, 10wt% Al in toluene solution) was obtained from Aldrich. The other commercially available reagents were purchased and utilized without further purification. FT-IR spectra were recorded on a NICOLET 5700 IR spectrometer. Elemental analyses were carried out using a Vario MICRO micro-analyzer. The viscosity-average molecular weights of the PNBs were calculated using Mark–Houwink coefficients at 25°C: α =0.56, K =7.78×10−4 dl/g [43]. TGA data was conducted with a METTLER TGA/SDTA851 thermal analysis system instrument under a nitrogen atmosphere up to 600°C at a heating rate of 10°C/min. Structural analysis of the resulting polymer was performed on a Phillips X’Pert SUPER powder X-ray diffractometer, with Cu Kα radiation (λ =1.5418Å) from 5.0° to 70.0°. 2.2 Norbornene polymerization In a typical procedure, catalyst (0.5μmol) and NB (0.98g) of dichloromethane solution were injected in a special polymerization bottle (25mL) under nitrogen atmosphere. The polymerization system was initiated by the adding appropriate MAO, and kept the total reaction volume to be 15mL. The polymerization reaction was carried out at an appropriate reaction temperature. Polymerization was terminated by adding acidic ethanol (ethanol/HCl: 95/5). The resulting PNBs were filtrated, washed with ethanol several times and dried in vacuum at 80°C to a constant weight. 2.3 X-ray structure determination Single crystal X-ray diffraction studies for 3a–c and 3e–f were performed on SCX Mini MERCURY2 diffractometer equipped with a graphite-monochromatized Mo-Kα radiation (λ =0.71073Å) at 293K. Cell parameters were obtained by global refinement of the positions of all collected reflections. Intensities were corrected for Lorentz and polarization effects and empirical absorption. The structures were solved by direct methods and refined by full-matrix least squares on F 2. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. The hydrogen atoms were placed in calculated positions. Structure solution and refinement were performed using the SHELX 97 package [44]. 2.4 Preparation and characterization 2.4.1 Synthesis of ligands Formylation of benzoylacetone (1): Benzoylacetone (3.24g, 20mmol) and trimethyl orthoformate (4.0mL, 35mmol) were dissolved in acetic anhydride (7.0mL, 60mmol) refluxing at 120°C for 5h. The diethyl ether was added into the mixture to obtain the precipitate. The product was further purified by recrystallizing (toluene) to afford white solid of 2-formyl-1-phenyl-1,3-dioxobutane in 41% yield. Treatment of benzoylacetone with trimethyl orthoformate and aceticanhydride provided 2-formyl-1-phenyl-1,3-dioxobutane (1), which reacted with o-phenylenediamine, ethylenediamine or trans-1,2-cyclohexanediamine to form the corresponding ligands (2a–c) according to the literature [45]. Ligands (2a–c) were treated with 2 equiv. of sodium hydroxide and were subsequently treated with an equimolar amount of NiCl2 or Cu(acac)2 to afford the corresponding complexes (3a–f) under nitrogen atmosphere [46]. All complexes were characterized by FT-IR and elemental analysis. According to the IR spectra, the CO stretching vibration of complexes 3a, 3c, 3d, and 3f shifted to higher values (1629–1639cm−1) with weaker intensity than their corresponding free ligands (1612–1619cm−1), while for complexes 3b and 3e, the CO stretching frequencies shifted toward lower values relative to the corresponding free ligand. The results indicate that there are coordination interactions between the O atoms of the ketone groups and central metal cation. In addition, complexes 3a–c and 3e–f were further confirmed by single crystal X-ray diffraction analysis. Crystals of complexes 3a–c and 3e–f suitable for single crystal X-ray analysis were obtained by slow evaporation from ethanol/dichloromethane solution at ambient temperature. Crystal data and processing parameters for 3a–c and 3e–f are listed in Table 1 . The molecular structures are shown in Figs. 1–5 , and the selected bond lengths and angles are listed in Table 2 . In the structure, there are two six-membered rings and one five-membered ring forming between the central metal and tetradentate ligand, and constituting of an almost square planar geometry. The different R groups of ligands have an obvious influence on the molecular structure. For nickel complexes 3a–c, it is noteworthy that complex 3c exhibits much longer bond lengths of Ni1-O1, Ni1-O2 than those of complexes 3a and 3b, although they display similar bond distances of Ni1-N2, Ni1-N1. Complexes 3b and 3c exhibit longer O1-C9 bond distance than complex 3a. The CN bonds for complex 3b exhibit a shorter distances relative to the corresponding bonds of complexes 3a and 3c. Moreover, among the nickel(II) complexes the CC bond lengths in chelate ring are between the normal CC single and double bonds, and the bonds of complex 3c are longest. The results suggest that the conjugation π-system exists in the β-ketoiminato nickel(II) complexes, and the bond lengths are slightly longer than the bis(β-ketoamino) nickel(II) complex reported previously [38]. The angles around the central nickel of the complexes 3a–c are nearly the same. However, the difference concerning the angles of N(1)-Ni(1)-O(2) and O(1)-Ni(1)-N(2) cannot be ignored. Complex 3b shows narrowest angles among the nickel(II) complexes, indicating that complex 3b has the largest distortion in the nickel coordination plane. As a result, the dihedral angles of the planes (O1, Ni1, N1) and (O2, Ni1, N2) of complex 3b (6.850(76)°) are much larger than those of complexes 3a (0.328(135)°) and 3c (1.946(77)°). As shown in Figs. 4 and 5, the molecular structures of copper(II) complexes 3e and 3f are similar to those of nickel(II) complexes 3b and 3c. Although complexes 3e and 3f display similar CuN2 bond distance, the other bond distances associated with the central metal copper are rather different. Compared with complex 3e, complex 3f has longer bond distances of Cu1O2 and Cu1N1, shorter Cu1O1 bond distance. Besides, there are many differences in CO bond distances for complexes 3e and 3f. Especially, the CN bond distances (1.317(11)Å and 1.208(13)Å) for complex 3e are very different from those of complex 3f (1.288(3)Å and 1.302(3)Å). The π-conjugation system existed in copper(II) complexes is similar to the nickel(II) complexes. In addition, the bond angles around central copper resemble the nickel(II) complexes, which are close to right angle (see Table 2). 3.2 Norbornene polymerization With MAO as cocatalyst, nickel(II) complexes 3a–c can polymerize NB to afford vinyl-typed PNB with high activities (105–106 gPNB/molNi h) and high molecular weights of the PNBs (105 g/mol). While little activity is observed when copper(II) complexes is used as catalysis and only traces of PNBs are obtained. The structures of the complexes play an important role in NB polymerization. This result is reflected in the catalytic activity order 3b > 3a > 3c under the same condition (Fig. 6 ). It is found that electronic effects of the ligands do not play a role in the activities. Instead, the ligand steric effects obviously influence the catalytic activity. Complex 3b with lower steric substituent is more favorable for increasing the activities than complexes 3a and 3c. For a systematic investigation of the polymerization parameters, the catalytic system 3b/MAO is tested under various conditions, and the detailed results are summarized in Table 3 . The MAO is an essential activator to the polymerization of NB. Variation of the molar Al/Ni ratio from 1500 to 3500, the activity first increased and then decreased with an optimal ratio of 2500 (entries 1–5 in Table 3 and Fig. 7 ). At the same time, the molecular weights of the PNBs increased up to a molar Al/Ni ratio of 2000. Higher molar Al/Ni ratios lead to a lower values of the molecular weight. This results indicating that the MAO is also acted as a chain transfer agent in the polymerization process. The influence of the polymerization time is also investigated. When the polymerization times is varied from 15min to 75min, the conversion of NB increases from 32.53% to 77.14% and the catalytic activities reduce rapidly due to the decreasing NB concentration during the reaction (entries 3 and 6–9 in Table 3 and Fig. 8 ) [38,39]. The molecular weights of the resultant PNBs declined sharply at the same time. When the reaction temperature is changed from 0°C to 40°C, the highest catalytic activity of 24.46×105 gPNB/molNi h is obtained at a temperature of 20°C (entries 6 in Table 3). While the molecular weights of the PNBs decreases uniformly. Similar results have been described in the relative literatures [27,41]. Though the catalytic activities and molecular weights are different in the range of 0°C to 40°C, the values do not vary significantly (entries 6 and 10–13 in Table 3 and Fig. 9 ). All the obtained polymers catalyzed by β-ketoiminato nickel(II) complexes 3a–3c are soluble in organic solvent, for instance chlorobenzene. In the IR spectra, there are no traces of double bonds appearing at 1620–1680cm−1, especially 960cm−1, indicating that the resultant polymers are vinyl-typed PNBs [47]. The TG/DTG curve reveals that the obtained PNBs exhibit good thermostability under nitrogen, which are stable up to 460.28°C (Fig. 10 ). As show in the Fig. 11 , two broad reflection peaks at 2θ of 9.27° and 18.12° are ascribed to the characteristic peaks of non-crystalline, agreed well with the former literature [48,49]. 4 Conclusion Nickel(II) and copper(II) complexes bearing tetradentate β-ketoiminato ligands have been synthesized and characterized. The X-ray diffraction studies reveal that the central metal of all the complexes coordinated with [ONNO] atoms of the corresponding ligands, which adopts a distorted square planar geometry. In the presence of MAO, nickel(II) complexes have been found to be active catalysts of vinyl addition NB polymerization and yield high molecular weight PNBs, especially the complex 3b with the highest catalytic activity of 24.46×105 gPNB/molNi h. While copper(II) complexes only generated traces of polymers. Supplementary material CCDC 916984-916988 contain the supplementary crystallographic data for complexes 3a, 3b, 3c, 3e and 3f. coredata.dc:description: The series of nickel(II) and copper(II) complexes (3a–f) bearing tetradentate [ONNO] β-ketoiminato ligands, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-o-phenylenediamine 2a, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-ethylenediamine 2b, N,N′-bis(2-benzoyl-3-oxobutylidene)-trans-1,2-cyclohexanediamine 2c, have been synthesized and characterized. X-ray crystal structures of complexes 3a–c and 3e–f reveal that each central metal adopts an almost square planar coordination geometry. Upon activation with methylaluminoxane (MAO), the nickel(II) complexes 3a–c display high catalytic activities for the vinyl polymerization of norbornene (NB), yielding high molecular weights of the polynorbornene (PNB), especially the complex 3b (24.46×105 gPNB/molNi h). While copper(II) complexes 3d–f only traces of PNB are generated. The catalytic system 3b/MAO is chosen for further investigations under various polymerization parameters.
